Theorem (transfinite_induction_III):
  for all v0, (if v0 is a subclass of \ORDomega then (if \SETempty is an element of v0 and for all v1, (if v1 is an element of v0 then \ORDsucc( v1 ) is an element of v0) then v0 is equal to \ORDomega))
Proof:
  it is wrong that (\Phi is equal to \ORDomega)
  n is an element of \ORDomega and it is wrong that (n is an element of \Phi)
  \Phi' is equal to \Phi \SETdiff \SETsingleton{ n }
  \SETempty is an element of \Phi'
  Proof:
    \SETempty is an element of \Phi and it is wrong that (\SETempty is equal to n)
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Phi' then \ORDsucc( v0 ) is an element of \Phi')
  Proof:
    x is an element of \Phi'
    \ORDsucc( x ) is an element of \Phi
    it is wrong that (\ORDsucc( x ) is equal to n)
    Proof:
      \ORDsucc( x ) is equal to n
      it is wrong that (x is an element of \Phi)
      Proof:
        it is wrong that (n is an element of \Phi) and (if x is an element of \Phi then (n is equal to \ORDsucc( x ) and \ORDsucc( x ) is an element of \Phi))
      Qed.
      falsity holds
    Qed.
    \ORDsucc( x ) is an element of \Phi'
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \ORDomega then v0 is an element of \Phi')
  Proof:
    \Phi' is a subclass of \Ord
  Qed.
  n is an element of \Phi'
  falsity holds
Qed.

Theorem:
