Theorem:
  \ORDomega is a limit ordinal
Proof:
  \ORDomega is transitive
  Proof:
    \Phi is a class and (if \ORDomega is a set then \Phi is a set) and for all v0, (v0 is an element of \Phi iff (v0 is an element of \ORDomega and v0 is an object and for all v1, (if v1 is an element of v0 then v1 is an element of \ORDomega)))
    \SETempty is an element of \Phi
    for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Phi then \ORDsucc( v0 ) is an element of \Phi)
    Proof:
      n is an element of \Phi
      for all v0, (if v0 is an element of n then v0 is an element of \ORDomega)
      for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \ORDsucc( n ) then v0 is an element of \ORDomega)
      \ORDsucc( n ) is an element of \Phi
    Qed.
    \ORDomega is a subclass of \Phi
    \ORDomega is transitive
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \ORDomega then v0 is an ordinal number)
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \ORDomega then v0 is transitive)
  \ORDomega is an ordinal number
  \ORDomega is a limit ordinal
  Proof:
    it is wrong that (the thesis holds)
    it is wrong that (\ORDomega is equal to \SETempty)
    \ORDomega is a successor ordinal
    \alpha is an ordinal number and \ORDsucc( \alpha ) is equal to \ORDomega
    \alpha is an element of \ORDomega
    \ORDomega is equal to \ORDsucc( \alpha ) and \ORDsucc( \alpha ) is an element of \ORDomega
    falsity holds
  Qed.
Qed.

